{
  "What is the typical unit for measuring the rate of a chemical reaction in solution?": "",
  "joules per mole": "",
  "grams per second": "",
  "mol/L/s (M/s)": "",
  "liters per minute": "",
  "Reaction rates in solution are typically measured as the change in concentration per unit time, with units of mol/L/s or M/s.": "",
  "Which factor generally increases the rate of a chemical reaction?": "",
  "Increasing the concentration of reactants": "",
  "Removing a catalyst": "",
  "Decreasing the temperature": "",
  "Decreasing the surface area of a solid reactant": "",
  "Increasing the concentration of reactants provides more molecules per unit volume, leading to more frequent collisions and a faster reaction rate.": "",
  "How does increasing temperature affect the rate of most reactions?": "",
  "It increases the rate": "",
  "It decreases the rate": "",
  "It has no effect": "",
  "It stops the reaction": "",
  "Increasing temperature gives molecules more kinetic energy, resulting in more frequent and more energetic collisions, which increases the reaction rate.": "",
  "As a reaction progresses, what generally happens to its rate?": "",
  "It decreases as reactants are consumed": "",
  "It increases steadily": "",
  "It oscillates between fast and slow": "",
  "It remains constant": "",
  "As reactants are consumed, their concentrations decrease, leading to fewer molecular collisions and a decreasing reaction rate over time.": "",
  "How does grinding a solid reactant into a fine powder affect the reaction rate?": "",
  "It decreases the rate by reducing the mass": "",
  "It increases the rate by increasing the surface area": "",
  "It has no effect on the rate": "",
  "It changes the products of the reaction": "",
  "Grinding increases the surface area exposed to other reactants, allowing more collisions to occur simultaneously and increasing the reaction rate.": "",
  "Which of the following best describes the instantaneous rate of a reaction?": "",
  "The initial rate only": "",
  "The rate at a specific moment in time": "",
  "The rate at the end of the reaction": "",
  "The average rate over the entire reaction": "",
  "The instantaneous rate is the rate at a specific moment in time, determined by the slope of the tangent line to the concentration-time curve at that point.": "",
  "For the reaction A -> B, if the concentration of A decreases from 0.80 M to 0.60 M in 10 seconds, what is the average rate?": "",
  "0.002 M/s": "",
  "0.020 M/s": "",
  "0.20 M/s": "",
  "2.0 M/s": "",
  "Average rate = change in concentration / change in time = (0.80 - 0.60) / 10 = 0.20/10 = 0.020 M/s.": "",
  "Why does the nature of the reactants affect reaction rate?": "",
  "Because all molecules react at the same speed": "",
  "Because temperature is the only factor that matters": "",
  "Because bond strengths and molecular complexity vary between substances": "",
  "Because catalysts are always required": "",
  "Different substances have different bond strengths, electron configurations, and molecular complexities, which affect how easily bonds break and form during a reaction.": "",
  "For the reaction 2A -> B, if the rate of disappearance of A is 0.10 M/s, what is the rate of appearance of B?": "",
  "0.05 M/s": "",
  "0.50 M/s": "",
  "0.10 M/s": "",
  "Since 2 mol A produces 1 mol B, the rate of appearance of B is half the rate of disappearance of A: 0.10/2 = 0.05 M/s.": "",
  "Which method can be used to monitor the rate of a reaction that produces a gas?": "",
  "Changing the temperature continuously": "",
  "Measuring mass loss over time": "",
  "Adding more reactant": "",
  "Filtering the solution": "",
  "As gas escapes from an open reaction vessel, the mass decreases. Measuring mass loss over time gives data to calculate the reaction rate.": "",
  "What is a reaction rate?": "",
  "The change in concentration of a reactant or product per unit time": "",
  "The energy needed to start a reaction": "",
  "The total amount of product formed": "",
  "The temperature at which a reaction occurs": "",
  "Reaction rate is the change in concentration of a reactant or product per unit time, measuring how fast a reaction proceeds.": "",
  "What does 'average rate' mean in the context of chemical kinetics?": "",
  "The rate at equilibrium": "",
  "The fastest rate achieved during the reaction": "",
  "The change in concentration divided by the change in time over a finite interval": "",
  "The rate measured at exactly one instant": "",
  "The average rate is calculated over a finite time interval by dividing the total change in concentration by the elapsed time.": "",
  "What does 'initial rate' mean?": "",
  "The rate after the reaction reaches equilibrium": "",
  "The rate measured just as the reaction begins, before significant reactant depletion occurs": "",
  "The slowest rate of the reaction": "",
  "The initial rate is the instantaneous rate measured at the very beginning of a reaction (time near zero), before reactant concentrations have changed significantly.": "",
  "What does 'chemical kinetics' mean?": "",
  "The study of molecular structures": "",
  "The study of chemical equilibrium": "",
  "The branch of chemistry concerned with the rates and mechanisms of chemical reactions": "",
  "The study of energy changes in reactions": "",
  "Chemical kinetics is the branch of chemistry that studies how fast reactions occur, the factors that affect reaction rates, and the step-by-step mechanisms by which reactions proceed.": "",
  "What does 'rate of disappearance' mean?": "",
  "How fast a product forms": "",
  "The rate at which a reactant's concentration decreases over time": "",
  "The speed at which molecules evaporate": "",
  "The time it takes for a catalyst to work": "",
  "The rate of disappearance measures how quickly the concentration of a reactant decreases over time as it is consumed in the reaction.": "",
  "What does 'rate of appearance' mean?": "",
  "The rate at which a product's concentration increases over time": "",
  "The time until a precipitate appears": "",
  "The rate at which a reaction starts": "",
  "The rate at which reactants collide": "",
  "The rate of appearance is the rate at which a product's concentration increases over time as it is formed during the reaction.": "",
  "What does 'concentration' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "The amount of solute dissolved per unit volume of solution": "",
  "The mass of the solvent only": "",
  "The total volume of a solution": "",
  "The temperature of the solution": "",
  "Concentration is the amount of solute dissolved in a given volume of solution, commonly expressed in molarity (mol/L).": "",
  "What does 'surface area' mean in the context of reaction rates?": "",
  "The area under a rate curve": "",
  "The cross-sectional area of a molecule": "",
  "The area of the container holding the reaction": "",
  "The total exposed area of a solid reactant available for contact with other reactants": "",
  "In reaction kinetics, surface area refers to the exposed area of a solid reactant that is in contact with other reactants; greater surface area allows more collisions and faster reactions.": "",
  "What does 'rate-determining step' mean?": "",
  "The step where the catalyst is regenerated": "",
  "The fastest step in a multi-step mechanism": "",
  "The slowest step in a reaction mechanism that determines the overall rate": "",
  "The final step in any reaction": "",
  "The rate-determining step is the slowest elementary step in a multi-step reaction mechanism, acting as a bottleneck that controls the overall rate of the reaction.": "",
  "What does 'molarity' mean?": "",
  "The number of particles per milliliter": "",
  "The number of moles of solute per liter of solution": "",
  "The ratio of solute to solvent by mass": "",
  "The mass of solute in grams per liter": "",
  "Molarity (M) is defined as the number of moles of solute dissolved per liter of solution, and is the most common concentration unit in reaction rate studies.": "",
  "A student dissolves an effervescent tablet in cold water and another in hot water. The tablet in hot water dissolves much faster. Which factor best explains this observation?": "",
  "The tablet has less surface area in hot water": "",
  "The hot water has a higher concentration of dissolved gas": "",
  "The cold water contains more catalyst": "",
  "Higher temperature increases molecular kinetic energy and collision frequency": "",
  "Higher temperature increases the kinetic energy of water molecules, leading to more frequent and more energetic collisions with the tablet, dissolving it faster.": "",
  "A steel wool pad burns slowly in air but bursts into bright flames when placed in pure oxygen. What factor primarily explains the difference in reaction rate?": "",
  "The steel wool has less surface area in oxygen": "",
  "Pure oxygen acts as a catalyst": "",
  "The concentration of oxygen is much higher, increasing collision frequency": "",
  "The temperature is higher in pure oxygen": "",
  "Pure oxygen has a much higher O2 concentration than air (which is only 21% O2), leading to far more frequent collisions between iron atoms and oxygen molecules.": "",
  "A food processing company notices that fruit stored at 4 degrees C spoils much more slowly than fruit at 25 degrees C. Based on kinetics, approximately how many times slower might the spoilage reactions be at 4 degrees C?": "",
  "About the same rate": "",
  "About 100 times slower": "",
  "About 4-8 times slower": "",
  "About 2-4 times slower": "",
  "A common rule of thumb is that reaction rates roughly double for every 10 degrees C increase. With a 21-degree difference, the rate would be approximately 2^2 to 2^2.1 = 4-8 times slower at the lower temperature.": "",
  "A chemist monitors a reaction by measuring the color intensity of a solution over time. The solution starts dark purple and becomes lighter. What can the chemist conclude about the reaction rate from this experiment?": "",
  "The temperature is increasing": "",
  "The rate cannot be determined from color changes": "",
  "The product is colored and accumulating": "",
  "The colored reactant is being consumed, and the rate of color fading reflects the reaction rate": "",
  "If the solution becomes lighter, a colored reactant is being consumed. Spectrophotometry can track this decrease in absorbance over time to measure the reaction rate.": "",
  "A sugar cube dissolves slowly in water, but the same mass of granulated sugar dissolves much faster. A student claims this is because granulated sugar is a different chemical. Is the student correct?": "",
  "No, the granulated sugar has more surface area exposed to water, increasing the dissolution rate": "",
  "Yes, the cube form is a different crystal structure": "",
  "No, but it dissolves faster because it is lighter": "",
  "Yes, granulated sugar has weaker bonds": "",
  "Both are the same substance (sucrose). Granulated sugar has a much larger total surface area than a sugar cube of the same mass, allowing more water contact and faster dissolution.": "",
  "A laboratory experiment measures the volume of gas produced every 30 seconds. The data shows: 0s = 0 mL, 30s = 25 mL, 60s = 40 mL, 90s = 48 mL, 120s = 50 mL. What does this data reveal about the reaction rate?": "",
  "The rate is constant throughout": "",
  "The rate increases over time": "",
  "The rate decreases over time as reactants are consumed": "",
  "The reaction has not started yet": "",
  "The gas volume produced per interval decreases (25, 15, 8, 2 mL), indicating the reaction rate slows as reactants are consumed over time.": "",
  "An enzyme in the human body speeds up the decomposition of hydrogen peroxide by a factor of 10^7. Without the enzyme, the reaction would take years. This enzyme is an example of what type of rate-affecting factor?": "",
  "Increasing concentration": "",
  "Increasing temperature": "",
  "Increasing surface area": "",
  "A biological catalyst": "",
  "The enzyme catalase is a biological catalyst that dramatically lowers the activation energy for H2O2 decomposition, increasing the rate by a factor of about 10 million.": "",
  "A coal dust explosion in a mine is much more violent than burning a lump of coal. Both involve the same reaction: C + O2 -> CO2. What explains the dramatic difference in rate?": "",
  "The temperature in a mine is always higher": "",
  "Coal dust has an enormously greater surface area, allowing rapid simultaneous reactions": "",
  "The mine has a higher concentration of oxygen": "",
  "Coal dust has a different chemical composition": "",
  "Fine coal dust particles have an extremely large surface area compared to a lump of coal. This allows the combustion reaction to occur simultaneously across millions of tiny particles, producing an explosive rate.": "",
  "A researcher runs an experiment where the initial rate is 0.050 M/s. After doubling the concentration of the reactant, the initial rate becomes 0.100 M/s. What does this tell us about the reaction?": "",
  "The reaction is first-order with respect to the reactant": "",
  "The reaction is zero-order with respect to the reactant": "",
  "The reaction does not depend on concentration": "",
  "The reaction is second-order with respect to the reactant": "",
  "When the concentration doubles and the rate also doubles (0.050 to 0.100 M/s), the reaction is first-order with respect to that reactant (rate is proportional to [A]^1).": "",
  "A car's catalytic converter speeds up the conversion of toxic NO and CO gases to harmless N2 and CO2. If the converter becomes coated with lead deposits, the reaction rate drops significantly. Why?": "",
  "Lead deposits block active catalyst sites, reducing the catalytic surface area available": "",
  "Lead increases the activation energy": "",
  "Lead absorbs all the heat from the exhaust": "",
  "Lead changes the products of the reaction": "",
  "Lead deposits coat and block the active sites on the platinum/palladium catalyst surface, preventing reactant molecules from adsorbing and reacting. This is called catalyst poisoning.": ""
